We thank the reviewer for a summary that captures the contribution more
accurately than we managed to state it ourselves. The central criticism --- that
the reader cannot tell which examples genuinely require split VEB and which are
already tractable under standard CAVI --- is correct, and we believe it explains
why the paper reads as harder than it should. We have restructured the relevant
material accordingly.

---

## W1 & Q1. Which examples need split VEB, and why is CAVI expensive?

The reviewer's observation about Eqs. (10)--(11) is exactly right: for those
prior families, conventional methods *can* compute efficiently. We conflated
cases where split VEB is a convenience with cases where it is a necessity, and
the resulting presentation obscured the contribution.

**Why the coupling arises.** The mechanism deserves a plain statement in the
main text, which it currently lacks. Under direct CAVI on the target model
(Corollary A.7), the M-step solves

$$
\hat\theta = \arg\max_\theta \prod_{j=1}^p \int
\mathcal{N}\!\left(\hat\beta_{j,\mathrm{MLE}};\, \beta_j,\, s_j^2\right)
g(\beta_j; d_j, \theta)\, d\beta_j ,
\qquad
\hat\beta_{j,\mathrm{MLE}} = x_j^\top \bar r_j / (n-1).
$$

The difficulty is in the sufficient statistic. Since
$\bar r_j = y - \sum_{j' \neq j} x_{j'}\bar\beta_{j'}$, updating *any* single
coordinate changes $\hat\beta_{j',\mathrm{MLE}}$ for *every* other $j'$, so the
objective above changes after each coordinate update and $\hat\theta$ must be
refit. With a closed-form M-step this is cheap; with a neural network it means
$p$ forward--backward passes per sweep.

Nash breaks this by feeding the M-step the shrinkage estimate
$\bar\beta_j = \omega\hat\beta_{j,\mathrm{MLE}} + (1-\omega)\bar b_j$, which is a
smooth function of $\bar b_j$ and can be updated for all $p$ coordinates *before*
the network is retrained --- hence one batched M-step per sweep.

\rev{Revision: the two paragraphs above have been promoted from Appendix A.3
into Section 3.2, immediately after Eq. (7), with the appendix retained for the
