**Which examples require it.** We have added the table the reviewer asks for.

| Prior family | M-step under direct CAVI | Cost per sweep | Split VEB needed? |
|:--|:--|:--|:--|
| Constant $\pi$ (ash / mr.ash) | Closed form (EBNM) | $\mathcal{O}(Kp)$ | No --- CAVI is efficient |
| Group one-hot, linear $\pi$ | Closed form per group (multinomial) | $\mathcal{O}(Kp)$ | No --- CAVI is efficient |
| Group one-hot, MLP $\pi$ (Eq. 10--11) | Iterative; requires NN fit | $\mathcal{O}(p)$ backward passes | Yes |
| Continuous index, MDN (Eq. 15) | Iterative; requires NN fit | $\mathcal{O}(p)$ backward passes | Yes |
| Graph / fused GNN prior (Eq. 13--14) | Iterative; neighbourhood-coupled | $\mathcal{O}(p)$ backward passes, non-local | Yes --- and impractical at MNIST scale |

\rev{This is now Table 2 in Section 4, and each example paragraph in Section 4
carries an explicit marker indicating which row it belongs to.}

To be direct about it: the ash and group-linear cases are included because they
show Nash *subsumes* existing penalties, not because it is needed for them.
mr.ash already handles the first efficiently, and we should have said so. The
contribution is confined to the last three rows, where the prior is an arbitrary
learned function of $d_j$ --- and the MNIST experiment (Section 5.5) is the case
where standard CAVI is not merely slow but infeasible, since the prior couples
each pixel to its neighbours through a two-layer message-passing network.

